definition.value: A bioconjugate obtained by coupling of (8Z,11Z,14Z)-icosatrienoic acid to another biomolecule (e.g. coenzyme A, an acyl-carrier protein, a phospholipid, an oligosaccharide, a nucleic acid etc.), which for the sake of convenience, is represented by an R group.

A bioconjugate obtained by coupling of alpha-linolenic acid to another biomolecule (e.g. coenzyme A, an acyl-carrier protein, a phospholipid, an oligosaccharide, a nucleic acid etc.), which for the sake of convenience, is represented by an R group.

A bioconjugate obtained by coupling of stearidonic acid to another biomolecule (e.g. coenzyme A, an acyl-carrier protein, a phospholipid, an oligosaccharide, a nucleic acid etc.), which for the sake of convenience, is represented by an R group.

A bioconjugate obtained by coupling of linoleic acid to another biomolecule (e.g. coenzyme A, an acyl-carrier protein, a phospholipid, an oligosaccharide, a nucleic acid etc.), which for the sake of convenience, is represented by an R group.

A bioconjugate obtained by coupling of gamma-linolenic acid to another biomolecule (e.g. coenzyme A, an acyl-carrier protein, a phospholipid, an oligosaccharide, a nucleic acid etc.), which for the sake of convenience, is represented by an R group.

A bioconjugate obtained by coupling of omega-3-arachidonic acid to another biomolecule (e.g. coenzyme A, an acyl-carrier protein, a phospholipid, an oligosaccharide, a nucleic acid etc.), which for the sake of convenience, is represented by an R group.

A bioconjugate obtained by coupling of timnodonic acid to another biomolecule (e.g. coenzyme A, an acyl-carrier protein, a phospholipid, an oligosaccharide, a nucleic acid etc.), which for the sake of convenience, is represented by an R group.
A heterotetracyclic stilbenoid that is a homodimer obtained by cyclodimerisation of resveratrol.
An indane-derived stilbenoid that is a homodimer obtained by cyclodimerisation of resveratrol.
A benzofuran-derived stilbenoid that is a homotrimer obtained by cyclotrimerisation of resveratrol.

A bioconjugate obtained by coupling of palmitic acid to another biomolecule (e.g. coenzyme A, an acyl-carrier protein, a phospholipid, an oligosaccharide, a nucleic acid etc.), which for the sake of convenience, is represented by an R group.

A bioconjugate obtained by coupling of sapienic acid to another biomolecule (e.g. coenzyme A, an acyl-carrier protein, a phospholipid, an oligosaccharide, a nucleic acid etc.), which for the sake of convenience, is represented by an R group.
A benzofuran-derived stilbenoid that is a homotrimer obtained by cyclotrimerisation of resveratrol. It is isolated from Dryobalanops oblongifolia.
A long-chain unsaturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of sapienic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

An organic sodium salt having loxoprofen(1-) as the counterion. The parent acid, loxoprofen, is a prodrug that is rapidly converted to its active trans-alcohol metabolite following oral administration.
An oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of loxoprofen, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

A pyridinemonocarboxylic acid that is nicotinic acid substituted at position 2 by a (2-methyl-3-chlorophenyl)amino group. Used (as its lysine salt) for treatment of renal colic, muscular pain and moderately severe migraine attacks.
An organoammonium salt obtained by combining clonixin with one molar equivalent of L-lysine. Used for treatment of renal colic, muscular pain and moderately severe migraine attacks.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and imido groups of riboflavin cyclic-4',5'-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of clonixin, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

A monocarboxylic acid that is propionic acid in which one of the hydrogens at position 2 is substituted by a 4-[(2-hydroxycyclopentyl)methyl]phenyl group (the 2S,1'R,2'S-stereoisomer. The active metabolite of loxoprofen.
Any metabolite produced by metabolism of a xenobiotic compound.

A member of the class of pyrazoles that is 1H-pyrazole which is substituted at positions 1, 3 and 5 by 4-sulfamoylphenyl, trifluoromethyl and 4-fluorophenyl groups, respectively. A selective cyclooxygenase 2 inhibitor, it is used in veterinary medicine to treat pain and inflammation in dogs with degenerative joint disease.

A sulfide salt with formula Na2S. The pentahydrate and  (particularly) the nonahydrate are also known. In gel form, sodium sulfide is used to soften toenails to assist in trimming (and so relive pain) of ingrowing toenails.
A hydrate with formula Na2S.9H2O.
An organonitrogen heterocyclic compound that is ajmaline which is lacking the methyl substituent attached to the nitrogen of the dihydroindole moiety.
A tertiary amino compound in which the para positions of the three phenyl rings in triphenylmethane are substituted with two dimethylamino groups and one hydroxy group.
An organic cation formed by loss of a proton from the central carbon of triphenylmethane.
A triarylmethane in which the three aryl groups are phenyl. It forms the basic skeleton of several synthetic dyes.

An iminium ion consisting of malachite green cation, substituted at the para position of the otherwise unsubstituted phenyl group with a diethylene glycol diamine linker, the terminal amino group of which may form part of a fluorogen activating protein (FAP).
Any benzenoid aromatic compound containing three aryl groups connected by a single C atom.
A straight-chain saturated fatty acid that is dotriacontane in which one of the methyl groups has been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acid.
A straight-chain saturated fatty acid that is tetratriacontane in which one of the methyl groups has been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acid.
A 2-hydroxy fatty acid that is the (R)-2-hydroxy derivative of octacosanoic acid.
A 2-hydroxy fatty acid that is the (R)-2-hydroxy derivative of hexacosanoic acid.
A non-fluorescent small compound which become fluorescent only when complexed to a fluorogen activating protein (FAP).

A member of the class of xanthones that is 9H-xanthen-9-one substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 1, 3, 6 and 7. Isolated from Garcinia mangostana and Maclura pomifera, it exhibits inhibitory activity against protein kinase C.
An omega-hydroxy fatty acid that is the 30-hydroxy derivative of triacontanoic acid.
An omega-hydroxy fatty acid that is the 32-hydroxy derivative of dotriacontanoic acid.
A ceramide that of sphingosine in which the 1-hydroxy and amino groups are carrying unspecified acyl substituents.
A member of the class of pyrrolizines that is 2,3-dihydro-1H-pyrrolizine which is substituted at positions 1 and 5 by carboxy and benzoyl groups, respectively.
A ketone in which the carbonyl group is attached to an aromatic ring.
A monoglyceride in which the acyl group is located at position 3 with an additional alkyl substituent at position 1.
A dihydroceramide in which the ceramide N-acyl group is specified as hexanoyl.

A 5-benzoyl-2,3-dihydro-1H-pyrrolizine-1-carboxylic acid that has R configuration. Unlike the S-enantiomer, it does not exhibit COX1 and COX2 inhibition, but does exhibit analgesic activity. Racemic ketorolac, known simply as ketorolac, is used (mainly as a tromethamine salt) as a potent analgesic for the short-term management of post-operative pain, and in eye drops to relieve the ocular itching associated with seasonal allergic conjunctivitis.

A 5-benzoyl-2,3-dihydro-1H-pyrrolizine-1-carboxylic acid that has S configuration. While (S)-ketorolac is a COX1 and COX2 inhibitor, both enantiomers exhibit analgesic effects. Racemic ketorolac, known simply as ketorolac, is used (mainly as the tromethamine salt) as a potent analgesic for the short-term management of post-operative pain, and in eye drops to relieve the ocular itching associated with seasonal allergic conjunctivitis.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxy group of ketorolac. The major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the removal of the proton from the carboxy group of meclofenamic acid. The major species at pH 7.3.
A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the acyl group is specified as oleoyl.
